","1342":"1342","about 1242":"circa 1242","1405":"1405","Anlaby, Yorkshire, England":"Anlaby, Yorkshire, England","of Anlaby, Yorkshire, England":"Anlaby, Yorkshire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Driffield, Yorkshire, England":"Driffield, Yorkshire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk"},"en":{"Abt 1202–":"about 1202–Deceased","1202–Male":"1202–Deceased","1204–Male":"1204–Deceased","1206–Female":"1206–Deceased","1233–Male":"1233–Deceased","1235–Male":"1235–Deceased","1242–1305":"1242–1305","1342–1405":"1342–1405","1171–1220":"1171–1220","1175–Female":"1175–Deceased","1220":"1220","1242":"1242","1175":"1175","Abt 1202":"about 1202","Abt 1235":"about 1235","1171":"1171","1305":"1305","1206":"1206","1204":"1204","Abt 1201":"about 1201","1235":"1235","1202":"1202","Abt 1233":"about 1233","Abt 1232":"about 1232","1233":"1233","1342":"1342","about 1242":"about 1242","1405":"1405","Anlaby, Yorkshire, England":"Anlaby, Yorkshire, England","of Anlaby, Yorkshire, England":"Anlaby, Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom","Driffield, Yorkshire, England":"Driffield, Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Legard","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (Yorkshire): from the Middle English male or female personal name <i>Legard</i> (Old French <i>Legard</i>, from ancient Germanic <i>Leudgard</i>, <i>Liudgard</i>, or its female equivalent <i>Leudgarda</i>, <i>Liudgarda</i>). These derive from the elements <i>leud</i> ‘people’ + <i>gard</i> ‘protective enclosure, yard’.","French: metonymic occupational name for a gardener or status name for someone who owned garden, a variant of   Gard  , with fused masculine definite article <i>le</i>. Compare also   Alligood  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Leggett","meanings":["English and Scottish: occupational name from Middle English <i>legat</i>, <i>legate</i> ‘delegate, ambassador, deputy’ (Old French <i>legat</i>), Latin <i>legatus</i> ‘one who is appointed or ordained’.","English: variant of   Legard  , especially in Sussex, perhaps through confusion of the two names."]},{"name":"Gard","meanings":["English (southern): occupational name from Middle English <i>gard(e)</i>, <i>guard(e)</i> ‘care, custody, protection’ (Old French <i>garde</i> ‘guard, watchman’), for a member of a town watch or troop of guards.","Norwegian (also <b>Gård</b>): habitational name from any of the two farmsteads so named in Rogaland, from Old Norse <i>garthr</i> ‘farm’.","Swedish (<b>Gård</b>): topographic or ornamental name from <i>gård</i> ‘farm’."]}]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When William Legard was born about 1202, in Anlaby, Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom, his father, John Legard, was 32 and his mother, Mrs John Rysome, was 29. He married Anne Legard about 1232. They were the parents of at least 4 sons."},"et":{"Abt 1202–":"umbes 1202–Surnud","1202–Male":"1202–Surnud","1204–Male":"1204–Surnud","1206–Female":"1206–Surnud","1233–Male":"1233–Surnud","1235–Male":"1235–Surnud","1242–1305":"1242–1305","1342–1405":"1342–1405","1171–1220":"1171–1220","1175–Female":"1175–Surnud","1220":"1220","1242":"1242","1175":"1175","Abt 1202":"umbes 1202","Abt 1235":"umbes 1235","1171":"1171","1305":"1305","1206